english:
  title: Memorial on Current Affairs
  author: Choi Seung-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I was born in the countryside and possess a dull and ignorant nature, lacking all learning. Yet by fortune I have lived in an enlightened age and long held minor office, receiving undeserved honors. Though I lack grand strategies to reform the times, I harbor a sincere wish to repay my country's kindness.

    I have observed how the historian Wu Jing of the Tang Dynasty compiled the *Zhenguan Zhengyao* to encourage Emperor Xuanzong to follow the governance of Emperor Taizong. Since their circumstances were similar, drawing from one tradition's success could serve as a model for all.

    Consider how our Great Ancestor founded the dynasty and established its line—what is called having ancestral merit. The successive kings who inherited and preserved what was built—what is called having kingly virtue. When the ancestor secured the state and home, he opened blessings for descendants. Yet the successors sometimes flourished and sometimes declined, unable to escape the failures of their time. The reason lies in how governance may fall into disorder, and deeds contain both good and evil. Often rulers fail to guard their end as carefully as their beginning, leading to peril and chaos. This is truly lamentable.

    Since our Great Ancestor opened the realm, all that I have witnessed remains fixed in my heart. I now respectfully record from five dynastic periods those instances of statecraft—both excellent and flawed—that may serve as mirror and warning.

    When our Great Ancestor, the Divine and Sagely King, ascended to the throne, though the age was chaotic, fortune aligned. He first subdued rebellion and destroyed the wicked. Heaven sent forth the previous ruler, yet borrowed his hand. Receiving the mandate and embracing the will of heaven, the people recognized his sacred virtue and gave their hearts. At that moment when the golden age of Silla passed away and the fortune of restoration dawned, without leaving his homeland he established a capital. He calmed the turbulent waters of the Yalu and Taedong rivers, recovered the lost lands of former Baekje and the Three Hans. In nineteen years he unified all lands under heaven. Surely no achievement was greater, no virtue more vast.

    Regarding the Khitans, whose borders touched ours, we should naturally have cultivated friendship first. Yet they sent envoys seeking peace, and we cut off relations. We did this because they had once allied with Balhae, then suddenly betrayed that bond through suspicion, causing its destruction in a single day. Therefore our Great Ancestor deemed them too lawless to befriend, and even rejected the camels they presented, refusing to raise them. His deep strategy and far-reaching plans—preventing calamity before it comes, preserving the realm before danger arrives—manifest in such measures.

    When Balhae fell to Khitan forces, its crown prince Daekwangbyeon and others, recognizing our nation's righteous cause, led tens of thousands of households in rapid flight to our borders. The Great Ancestor pitied them deeply and welcomed them with great courtesy. He even granted them surnames and attached them to our royal registers, allowing them to maintain the sacrifices to their ancestral homeland. All military and civil officials below them received honors and rank. His haste in preserving the perished, in restoring what had fallen—such was his virtue.

    When Gyeon Hwon of Baekje, savage and loving chaos, killed his lord and oppressed his people, upon hearing this our Great Ancestor could neither sleep nor rest. He sent forth armies to punish this crime and achieved restoration. His fidelity to the fallen lord, his care in raising the fallen state—such was his way.

    From the late Silla period until our founding, the western and northern frontier peoples suffered constant raids and theft from Jurchen horsemen. The Great Ancestor, judging carefully, dispatched one able general to suppress them. Without drawing a blade, he turned the barbarian multitudes to submission. Thereafter the frontier grew quiet and the borders secure. His wisdom in recognizing talent, his skill in using it—such was his mastery.

    The lords and ministers of Silla, knowing their fortune exhausted and their fate sealed, sought of their own accord to submit. Even after repeated requests for permission, only then did he consent. From Myeongju in the east to Heungnyebu, more than one hundred and ten cities—none failed to embrace his benevolence and answer his call in due season. His power to win submission through courtesy and yielding—such was his grace.

    Only in the south, against Baekje, did necessity compel the use of force. Though he raised armies several times, beneath his banners and before his horses, some would surrender at the gates while others would tremble at merely seeing his approach. Though blades clashed, he took no pleasure in slaughter. Truly, the virtuous have no enemies.

    After Gyeon Hwon accumulated wickedness for more than thirty years, he was finally imprisoned by his own treacherous underlings and fled to us, requesting military aid to punish the rebels. Upon hearing this, the Great Ancestor received him with generous courtesy. When Gyeon Hwon passed away, he was honored with lavish funeral gifts. His benevolence spanned from the visible to the invisible realm, his righteousness encompassed both the living and the dead.

    When Baekje was pacified and the royal procession entered the city, he showed compassion to impoverished people, offering generous comfort and reassurance. He commanded the armies to refrain from even minor violations. Since North and South had long been divided and old and new populations were different, the Great Ancestor treated them as one, never changing his approach. His broad tolerance, his ample forbearance—such was his nature.

    From unification onward, for eight years he cultivated governance with diligence. Toward great powers he practiced propriety; with neighbors he maintained righteousness. In peace he refused indolence; in dealing with inferiors he considered respect. He prized virtue and elevated frugality. His palaces were modest, providing merely shelter from wind and rain. His garments were simple, merely adequate against heat and cold. He loved the worthy and cherished goodness, surrendering his own will to follow others' counsel. His reverence, his restraint, his courtesy, his yielding—these flowed from his nature itself. Born among common people, he had experienced hardship and knew well the truth and falsehood in human hearts. In all matters of safety and danger, his foresight was clear. Thus rewards and punishments never missed their moment; the crooked and the straight never confused their paths. His understanding of encouragement and admonition, his grasp of kingly authority—such was his wisdom.

    Moreover, he recognized talent without losing it, commanded subordinates and gained their strength, trusted the worthy without wavering, dismissed the wicked without doubting, honored Buddhist teaching and valued Confucian learning. As a ruler his virtues were complete; as a founder his models could be followed. Yet since the early days of founding, his reign was brief. The royal ancestral shrines and state altars could not yet be glorified. Ritual and music, cultural refinement were still lacking. The ranks and ceremonies of all offices, both inner and outer, had not yet been properly established. His sudden passing—this was the nation's misfortune and heaven's inscrutability. Deeply lamentable.

    King Hyejong spent long years as crown prince, overseeing various affairs. He showed respect to his tutors and courtesy to officials, earning widespread praise throughout court and country. Upon ascending the throne, all rejoiced. At that time someone slandered Crown Prince Jeong and his brothers, suggesting they harbored treasonous intent. Hyejong heard but gave no answer, asked nothing, and increased his affection and favor toward them as before. Thus all admired his magnanimity.

    Yet soon he abandoned virtuous governance, became overly protective of his life, and kept armed guards constantly at his side—signs of excessive suspicion that betrayed the dignity of rulership. He granted unequal rewards to generals, his favors unevenly distributed, causing resentment both within and without as people's hearts turned away. Scarcely a year into his reign, severe illness overtook him. Confined to his sickbed for months, access to court officials and wise counselors was blocked while low-born attendants lingered in his chambers. His affliction worsened, his anger daily increased. For three years his people saw no benefit of his virtue. At last, upon his passing, he barely escaped catastrophe. Is this not cause for sorrow?

    When King Jeong was in the palace as a prince, he already enjoyed a good reputation. As Hyejong's illness grew grave, the prime minister Wang Gyu and others harbored secret designs, eyeing the royal household. Jeong perceived this first and quietly made plans with loyal generals from the western capital. When internal turmoil was about to erupt and the guard troops arrived in force, their schemes failed and the conspirators were executed. Though heaven's mandate was fulfilled, human strategy played its part. Was this not extraordinary? From King Jeong until now, thirty-eight years have passed. That the realm's fortune has not been severed owes much to Jeong's steadiness.

    Though King Jeong inherited through his collateral line, he was diligent day and night, eagerly seeking good governance. Sometimes he would light candles to receive court officials; sometimes he would delay his meals while attending to countless state affairs. Thus all rejoiced at his accession. Yet he fell prey to superstition about prophetic texts and resolved to move the capital. His rigid nature would not yield. Heavy taxation and forced labor oppressed the people. Though born of the ruler's intention, the common sentiment rebelled. Resentment arose and calamities followed swiftly as shadows. Before the capital could be moved westward, he departed from the throne forever. Truly lamentable.

    King Gwangjong possessed exceptional talent and outstanding gifts. He received the special affection of the Great Ancestor and the personal instruction of King Jeong. Upon succession he treated his subjects with ritual propriety and showed keen judgment in recognizing talent. He did not favor the close and powerful; he did not despise the distant and humble but extended his benevolence even to the widowed and childless. From his accession through eight years, governance was clear and rewards and punishments were fair.

    Yet after Ssanggi arrived, he elevated literary scholars excessively. His favors became excessive, so that the untalented advanced undeservedly, rising without following proper ranks. Men became chancellors almost overnight. Sometimes he would extend audiences deep into the night; sometimes he entertained visitors continuously. So focused was he on pleasure that he neglected state affairs. Military and national business became clogged and could not proceed. Feasting and entertainment continued without end. People from both north and south competed to gain his patronage. Without regard to wisdom or talent, all received special favor and courtesy. Thus rising officials competed for advancement while established virtues declined.

    Though he honored Chinese ways, he did not adopt China's excellent institutions. Though he treated Chinese scholars courteously, he did not gain their genuine talent. The common people suffered loss of their lifeblood; the four quarters gained only empty reputation. Neglecting governance, Gwangjong surrounded himself with flatterers. Suspicion deepened daily, communication between ruler and minister closed off. No one dared speak of the state's successes and failures.

    Moreover, he came to trust Buddhism excessively and overvalue Buddhist practice. Regular observances multiplied; separate devotions never ceased. He sought only longevity and blessing through prayer, squandering limited resources on endless causes. Fond of small acts of charity, yet in his comings and goings he indulged in extreme extravagance. Seeing no immediate calamity, he attributed this to Buddhist power, refusing to reform his conduct. His palaces exceeded proper limits, his clothing and food demanded rare treasures, construction work proceeded regardless of season, craftwork never ceased. Calculating his annual expenses, they sufficed for ten years under the Great Ancestor. In his later years he slew many innocents.

    I believe that had Gwangjong constantly practiced frugality and restraint as in his early years, his lifespan would not have been cut short to merely fifty years. That he could not persevere to the end—truly lamentable. Moreover, from the year Gyeongsin through the year Eulhae, sixteen years passed in which the treacherous prospered, slander flourished, the virtuous found no shelter, and the base achieved their aims. Sons rebelled against fathers, servants against masters; bond between superior and subordinate was severed, trust between ruler and minister dissolved.

    Old ministers and veteran generals were executed in succession; blood relatives were annihilated. If we consider the kindness Hyejong showed in preserving his brother and Jeong's skill in maintaining the realm, their grace was surely great. Both kings had but one son, yet neither could preserve his heir's life. Not only did they fail to repay their kindness; they deepened their resentment. In his final years, Gwangjong harbored suspicion even toward his own son. So King Gyeongjo in the eastern palace could never feel secure. Fortunate that he succeeded to the throne. Alas, how could he who began well and earned early renown end poorly and fall to such depths? Deeply sorrowful.

    King Gyeongjo was born deep within the palace and raised in women's hands. He had never seen affairs beyond the palace gates. Yet possessing natural acuity, in his father's final days he was able to avoid grave error and succeeded to the throne. Upon ascending, he burned the accumulated documents of slander and released the wrongfully imprisoned by the thousands. Resentments were cleared, wrongs righted, and court and country celebrated.

    Yet lacking understanding of governance, he relied entirely on powerful ministers. Harm fell upon royal relatives; portents of disaster appeared first. Though he later realized this, there was no one to blame. Thereafter the wicked and righteous were not distinguished, rewards and punishments were inconsistent. Before order could be achieved, he tired of diligence. He fell prey to sensuality, delighting in folk entertainment and increasingly absorbed in games. Alone with court eunuchs and palace attendants, the words of virtuous men found no entrance; the whispers of base men sometimes found hearing.

    Though he too earned early praise, his later years lacked worthy conduct. As it is said: "All things have beginnings; few achieve proper endings." What loyal minister or righteous scholar would not grieve? This the Sage has himself witnessed.

    Yet Gyeongjo possessed merit. When he first fell ill, before his condition became critical, from his sickbed he summoned the Sage, grasped his hand, and entrusted him with state affairs. This was blessing not merely for the shrines and altars but for the people as well.

    Only the last two kings inherited through the eastern palace, so no one harbored different hopes. Yet between brothers, without explicit succession, dispute must arise. Hyejong lay ill for two years before departing, leaving a young heir called the Heunghua Young Lord. Yet he could not entrust affairs to his brothers. Jeong, receiving the support of the ministers, inherited the realm. At his passing, he swiftly transmitted the throne to Gwangjong to settle the shrines and altars. The legacy of both Jeong and Gyeongjo appears clear.

    I have also observed how in the early days of Hyejong, Jeong, and Gwangjong's succession, when a hundred matters were still unsettled, half the civil and military officials of both capitals had already been slain. By Gwangjong's final years, as chaos spread and slander flourished, most bearing responsibility were actually innocent. Historical merit-holders and veteran generals all faced execution. When Gyeongjo ascended, scarcely forty surviving old officials remained. Many were slain in those days, though most were recent schemers scarcely worth mourning.

    Yet the two young lords of Cheonan and Jincheon were branches of the imperial line. Gwangjong had shown them clemency, refusing to prosecute them. By Gyeongjo's time they could have served as bulwarks of the state. Instead, they fell victim to treacherous ministers' plots and became wandering ghosts below the earth. How could this not grieve one's lineage? Many earlier kings failed to enjoy long lives because of such harms. Let later generations take warning.

    I humbly reflect that Your Highness, possessed of supreme sagacity, encounters this period of restoration. Receiving the gracious abdication of your predecessor, you have inherited the vast enterprises of all the enlightened kings. Not a single creature fails to rejoice in life; not one person fails to find his proper place. Within and without all celebrate together; humans and spirits alike offer congratulations. This is what is meant by "Heaven ordains it; the people sustain it."

    Should the Sage be able to follow the legacy of the Great Ancestor, how would this differ from Emperor Xuanzong's emulation of the Emperor Taizong's affairs?

    Moreover, should the Sage be able to examine and choose from the recent examples of these four kings: Hyejong showed the merit of preserving his brothers—this exemplifies supreme brotherly love. Jeong foresaw the seeds of rebellion and was able to quell palace intrigue, restoring the shrines and altars, transmitting down to the present day—this demonstrates clear judgment. Gwangjong's eight years of governance can rival the Three Dynasties. Court ceremonies and institutions possess noteworthy aspects—this shows balance in distributing merit and fault. Gyeongjo released thousands of wrongful convictions from previous reigns and burned years of accumulated slander—this represents supreme clemency and benevolence.

    These four kings' records of governance are broadly thus. The Sage should embrace their virtues and follow them, observe their failures and learn caution. Eliminate unnecessary tasks, cease fruitless labors. Simply ensure the ruler dwells in peace above and the people rejoice below. Maintain the care you showed in beginning well; aspire to complete it well. Guard yourself day after day. Though you rest, do not truly rest. Though you occupy the supreme throne, do not exalt yourself. Though rich in talent and virtue, do not become arrogant. Hold fast to personal respect and never abandon concern for the people. Then blessings will come unsought; calamities will depart unexorcised. Why should the Sage's life not span ten thousand years? Why should kingly enterprise last but a hundred?

    Though I am foolish and unworthy, I occupy a position of responsibility. Since I have thought to report and cannot avoid the duty, I have reverently recorded these humble reflections on current affairs—twenty-eight items in all—forwarding them in separate memorial.

    [The remaining twenty-five items detail specific proposals regarding border defense, elimination of wasteful Buddhist ceremonies, reduction of imperial household expenses, establishment of local officials, proper dress codes, curbing monastic privileges, regulation of construction according to rank, proper conduct of sacrifices, and equitable treatment of former nobles and their descendants.]
